Reorganize parsing

Since the beginning of HTTPolice, I have been trying to keep header parsing
and HTTP/1.x framing parsing together. Originally it was the exact same
mechanism. Later, when I switched to Earley parsing, it proved too
expensive for framing and I bolted on some regexes derived from the same
grammar combinators. Later came strange things like `simple_parse`.

Eventually it became clear to me that headers and framing are two very
different use cases and they should be separated, which I did in this
commit. The only thing they share now is the `ParseError`, and
the associated need for framing to have 'hollow' grammar symbols purely
for rendering these `ParseError`.

This makes the code simpler and clearer, but more importantly, it solves
the problem that we used to read entire TCP streams eagerly into memory
before even starting to parse them (because our regex engine cannot read
from a file on demand).

Overhaul httpolice.known

This commit brings several changes for the better.

- Data is now stored in CSV files as opposed to Python code. I don't
  have a very good argument for this, but in code it just seemed ugly.
  This really is pure data, after all. A major reason for why I stored
  it in code originally was to refer directly to grammar symbols
  instead of resolving them via `importlib` -- but that proved a bad
  idea in itself, see below.

- As a neat if trivial side effect of this, ``tools/iana.py`` now
  updates the files directly instead of listing the updates on stdout
  to be applied manually.

- References from `httpolice.known` to `httpolice.syntax` are now
  resolved lazily, which enables using the former from the latter
  directly. I thought there was a real need for this, but now that
  it's fixed, I could only remember this one place in ``rfc7231.py``.
  Maybe I missed something. In any case, it's the right factoring.

- Settle on the ``from httpolice import known`` syntax to disambiguate
  instances of `Knowledge` (such as `known.method`) from other objects
  in scope, making the code clearer and removing strange things like
  ``method as method_info``.

- While we're at it, there's no need for multiple citations per known
  entry, nor for the complex tuples-to-strings logic in `RFC`.
